To convert **Integer** to **long** use the **longValue()** method available in the Integer class.
Which returns the value of the Integer as a long after a widening primitive conversion.

Example:

     Integer intVal = 10;

     long longVal = intVal.longValue();

The problem is you do `int + int` which can be `long`. You should keep in the `Map` `long` value insted of `int`.

```java
public static long gridProblem(int m, int n, Map&lt;String, Long&gt; map) {
    if (n == 0 || m == 0) return 0;
    if (n == 1 &amp;&amp; m == 1) return 1;

    String s = m + &quot;,&quot; + n;

    if (map.containsKey(s)) return map.get(s);

    long nth = gridProblem(m - 1, n, map) + gridProblem(m, n - 1, map);
    map.put(s, nth);
    return nth;
}

public static void main(String... args) {
    Map&lt;String, Long&gt; h = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    System.out.println(gridProblem(11, 8, h));
}
```

***P.S.** I know that using recursion is quite intuitive and simple, but only for test tasks. For big input, you can get `StackOverflowError`. It&#39;s better to use iterations instead. Check this out!*
```java
public static long gridProblem(int rows, int cols) {
    int[][] b = new int[rows][cols];
    long sum = 0;

    for (int row = 0; row &lt; rows; row++) {
        for (int col = 0; col &lt; cols; col++) {
            if (row == 0 || col == 0) b[row][col] = 0;
            else if (row == 1 &amp;&amp; col == 1) b[row][col] = 1;
            else b[row][col] = b[row][col - 1] + b[row - 1][col];

            sum += b[row][col];
        }
    }

    return sum;
}
````

